  <h1>Why everything I touch is Solarized</h1>
  <p class="muted sans" style="font-size:var(--text-xs);">July 11, 2026</p>

  <p>
    Terminal, editor, tmux, prompt, SSH sessions into five different
    machines. Same sixteen colors every time: Solarized Dark. This site's
    palette above is the same hex values, pulled from the same source. Not
    a rut, one module.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ethan Schoonover built Solarized against actual color science rather
    than a screenshot someone liked. The eight monotone and eight accent
    colors are tuned in CIELAB space so contrast holds up consistently
    across both a light and a dark variant, instead of the muddy or
    blown-out swaps most palettes produce when you try to run them both
    ways. It reads as a spec, not a vibe.
  </p>

  <p>
    The personal reason is simpler: it's calming, and it cuts visual
    noise. One palette everywhere means my eyes stop re-adjusting every
    time I context-switch between tools.
  </p>

  <p>
    The engineering reason is why it stuck. The palette lives in one
    place, a Nix module, exposed as a single attrset every tool config
    reads from: terminal, editor, tmux, prompt, even the CSS variables
    behind this page. Switching theme, if I ever did, is a one-line import
    change in one file, not a dozen configs edited by hand and drifting
    out of sync a month later. The consistency isn't upkeep, it's
    structural.
  </p>

  <p>
    More about how I work: <a href="/">home</a>.
  </p>
</Base>
